00:40:04,960 --> 00:40:07,920
Close your eyes, unless you're driving that car with the solid steering wheel.

765
00:40:07,920 --> 00:40:09,680
Please keep your eyes open if you're driving.

766
00:40:09,840 --> 00:40:09,980
Right.

767
00:40:10,520 --> 00:40:15,580
Imagine you are looking at a cross-section of a star or maybe a massive atom.

768
00:40:16,120 --> 00:40:19,540
Right in the dead center, there is a brilliant white-yellow core.

769
00:40:20,080 --> 00:40:23,320
The paper labels this as a low-entropy singularity.

770
00:40:23,740 --> 00:40:26,020
It's a place of extreme tight coherence.

771
00:40:26,260 --> 00:40:29,360
That core is the deep harmonic lock we discussed.

772
00:40:29,620 --> 00:40:29,920
Right.

773
00:40:29,920 --> 00:40:35,560
Surrounding this bright core are nested rings, concentric circles like the layers of an onion.

774
00:40:36,140 --> 00:40:38,840
The paper calls these stabilization shells.

775
00:40:39,560 --> 00:40:42,020
Between these bright rings are dark gaps.

776
00:40:42,460 --> 00:40:48,300
These are nodal zones where the outgoing and incoming waves perfectly cancel each other out in destructive interference.

777
00:40:48,300 --> 00:40:52,880
The shells in the nodal zones represent the low eigenvalue modes of the field.

778
00:40:53,420 --> 00:40:57,060
This is the visual representation of the standing wave pattern of matter.

779
00:40:57,220 --> 00:40:58,600
But it gets so much more complex.

780
00:40:58,940 --> 00:41:03,900
Emanating from that bright central core are these vividly colored rays of light shooting outward.

781
00:41:04,440 --> 00:41:12,780
They range from low-frequency orange and red rays up through mid-frequency blue and violet all the way to high-frequency yellow and green rays.

782
00:41:12,940 --> 00:41:14,120
It's a very striking image.

783
00:41:14,120 --> 00:41:14,680
It is.

784
00:41:15,060 --> 00:41:19,560
These rays shoot outward from the core, traverse the shells, and hit an outer boundary.

785
00:41:19,920 --> 00:41:21,480
When they hit the boundary, they refract.

786
00:41:22,220 --> 00:41:25,600
They bounce back inward, traveling all the way back to hit the center core again.

787
00:41:25,820 --> 00:41:28,140
That visual of the refracting rays is crucial.

788
00:41:28,600 --> 00:41:34,280
It illustrates how propagative energy emitted from the concrescent core hits the confining limits of its environment,

789
00:41:34,900 --> 00:41:37,440
undergoes reflection, and re-enters the interior.

790
00:41:37,880 --> 00:41:39,380
So it feeds back into itself.

791
00:41:39,620 --> 00:41:39,960
Exactly.

792
00:41:40,120 --> 00:41:42,220
Each reflection reinforces the shell structure.

793
00:41:42,220 --> 00:41:46,800
The boundary is continuously returning energy back into the system in perfect phase,

794
00:41:46,980 --> 00:41:49,580
which is what sustains the standing wave over time.

795
00:41:49,980 --> 00:41:54,520
But the detail that completely fascinated me is the shape of that outer boundary.

796
00:41:55,080 --> 00:41:56,360
It is not a perfect circle.

797
00:41:56,620 --> 00:41:57,220
No, it's not.

798
00:41:57,300 --> 00:42:03,460
While the inner rings are perfectly round, the outermost shell is an anisotropic four-fold shape.

799
00:42:03,740 --> 00:42:05,260
It's slightly warped.

800
00:42:05,600 --> 00:42:09,580
It completely breaks the perfect rotational symmetry of the inner rings.

801
00:42:09,580 --> 00:42:11,800
Why is the boundary asymmetrical?

802
00:42:12,340 --> 00:42:13,720
To explain that asymmetry,

803
00:42:14,200 --> 00:42:18,140
Flyxion brings in the work of a brilliant French philosopher named Gilbert Simondon.

804
00:42:18,280 --> 00:42:18,560
Okay.

805
00:42:18,980 --> 00:42:23,480
Simondon provides a necessary, vital corrective to the idea of a perfect stabilization.

806
00:42:24,760 --> 00:42:29,540
If the system simply descended into a perfect, symmetrical, spherical attractor and stayed there,

807
00:42:29,940 --> 00:42:32,400
it would reach static thermodynamic equilibrium.

808
00:42:32,540 --> 00:42:33,800
Which means it stops moving.

809
00:42:33,800 --> 00:42:37,620
From a physics standpoint, perfect equilibrium is death.

810
00:42:37,900 --> 00:42:38,360
It's inert.

811
00:42:39,180 --> 00:42:46,760
Simondon insists that a living individual, whether that individual is an atom, a biological cell, a human memory, or an entire person,

812
00:42:47,080 --> 00:42:49,200
is never a perfectly stable substance.

813
00:42:49,980 --> 00:42:52,180
It is a metastable resolution of a field.

814
00:42:52,560 --> 00:42:56,460
Metastable, meaning it is stable enough to hold its shape and persist,

815
00:42:56,940 --> 00:42:59,640
but fragile enough to be capable of change.

816
00:42:59,640 --> 00:43:00,040
Exactly.

817
00:43:00,240 --> 00:43:06,000
It holds a charge, and the source of that capacity for change is what Simondon calls the pre-individual field.

818
00:43:06,200 --> 00:43:07,520
The pre-individual field.

819
00:43:07,660 --> 00:43:13,220
Visually, this is represented by that asymmetrical, four-fold boundary pushing against the perfect rings.

820
00:43:14,240 --> 00:43:17,300
Stabilization never exhausts all the potential of the universe.

821
00:43:17,760 --> 00:43:20,860
There is always structured, unresolved potential left over.

822
00:43:21,100 --> 00:43:21,880
Latent energy.

823
00:43:22,100 --> 00:43:26,080
There are hidden symmetries, latent relational tensions, and energetic capacities

824
00:43:26,080 --> 00:43:29,380
that have not yet been integrated into the object's current geometry.

825
00:43:29,380 --> 00:43:34,160
It's the friction of the outside world refusing to conform to the object's internal rules.

826
00:43:34,640 --> 00:43:35,340
That's a great way to put it.

827
00:43:35,520 --> 00:43:41,440
The system draws from this asymmetrical, pre-individual reservoir to sustain itself, but also to transform.

828
00:43:41,980 --> 00:43:43,060
It feeds on the tension.

829
00:43:43,360 --> 00:43:47,680
So, to stay alive, to persist as a coherent entity in this universe,

830
00:43:48,140 --> 00:43:50,580
a system actually needs to be slightly unresolved.

831
00:43:50,700 --> 00:43:52,180
It needs a degree of conflict.

832
00:43:52,520 --> 00:43:53,120
It does.

833
00:43:53,320 --> 00:43:58,120
If it achieves perfection, it ceases to exist as a dynamic process.

834
00:43:58,120 --> 00:44:02,280
If we zoom out to the ultimate philosophical implication of the paper, yes.

835
00:44:02,980 --> 00:44:06,900
Without that unresolved tension at the boundary, there is no engine for transformation.

836
00:44:07,660 --> 00:44:11,900
If the system reached perfect, symmetrical equilibrium, it would freeze into a dead rock.

837
00:44:11,980 --> 00:44:12,220
Right.

838
00:44:12,420 --> 00:44:16,220
On the opposite extreme, if there were no concentric rings of coherence at all,

839
00:44:16,380 --> 00:44:21,340
it would just be pure chaos, pure static noise, unable to sustain an identity.

840
00:44:21,340 --> 00:44:27,000
Which brings us all the way back full circle to Whitehead and his concept of the creative advance of the universe.

841
00:44:27,800 --> 00:44:30,120
Flyxion mathematically formalizes this, right?

842
00:44:30,500 --> 00:44:33,640
The paper introduces the variational principle of creative advance.

843
00:44:34,200 --> 00:44:37,420
The mathematics of the RSVP fields naturally reward novelty,

844
